post_text:
2020 Skyline Kids Running Basics Camp

The 2020 Skyline High and Middle School Cross Country teams will be holding a running basics camp for future T-Bird runners or those who want to come out and have fun! The running basics camp will be the High and Middle School Cross Country team’s fundraiser to help purchase team shirts and supplies for the upcoming cross country season.

The camp will be held July 13-17th from 7:00 to 8:00 PM at Skyline and is open to incoming 4th, 5th, and 6th graders. Topics will include stretching, strength training, running form, and games to increase speed and endurance. Water and a snack will be provided each evening.

The cost is $20.00 per child. Families with more than one child will receive a $5.00 discount on additional children ($15.00). Please make checks payable to Skyline Cross Country. Registration can be turned in at the front office at Skyline.

If you have any questions, please contact Coach Neifert (mneifert@skylineschools.org) or Coach Lucas (plucas@skylineschools.org).

post_text:
Due to continued concerns with Covid-19 and the changes in our school year, Skyline will not be holding a sports physical clinic this year. Each student entering grades 7-12 in 2020/2021 who plan to participate in sports or cheer will be responsible for scheduling their own sports physical with their family doctor prior to the start of practice next school year. Cheerleaders are required to have their physicals completed before summer cheer camp. Physicals can be scheduled after May 1st.
Please check your email for a link to the KSHSAA website to print off a physical form. KSHSAA has made some changes to the form this year, so please make sure it is filled out and signed completely before returning to the school. Also in the email is the concussion form. Please have this completed along with your physical and return both forms to Skyline Schools c/o Amy Swonger.

post_text:
Just a reminder to all of our students, parents, players, coaches, and fans, not only are our boys competing for a state championship this week, but our entire school will be competing for the KSHSAA Sportmanship award. Now is a great time to be reminded to only cheer positively for our team. Never cheer in a negative manor directed towards the opposing team. Let the officials do their job and let’s do ours of supporting our team. In all my years, I’ve never seen an official change their call because the crowd complains. If anything, it works against our team and doesn’t represent the school well. Let’s bring home a State Championship AND a KSHSAA Sportsmanship Award for Skyline! Good luck to the coaches and team this week. We are all super proud of you!

A sample ballot is attached below and categories will include the following:
1) Cheer Squad
2) Students Body/Pep Club/Pep Band
3) Players and Managers
4) Coaches
5) Adults/Parents/Non-HS Fans

Last Friday, Skyline 6th grade K-Kids sent out the packets for Reading for Education Fundraising. These are the packets that ask you to share the addresses of your friends and family. The cards that are filled out either by students or parents are then sent directly to the recipients and they are given the option to buy magazines at discounted prices. The company guarantees that these addresses are not being sold to a third party. The school benefits from about $0.50 for every completed card. This money is used to supplement extra-curricular and service projects (special car seat for a diabled student, buddy bench, snacks for after school programs, etc.).

Monday, February 3 is the final turn in day. Completed booklets equal fun prizes, but partially filled booklets are accepted. Please also return any unfilled booklets. If you have any questions, please direct them to Mr. Nelson at mnelson@skylineschools.org.
text:
Last Friday, Skyline 6th grade K-Kids sent out the packets for Reading for Education Fundraising. These are the packets that ask you to share the addresses of your friends and family. The cards that are filled out either by students or parents are then sent directly to the recipients and they are given the option to buy magazines at discounted prices. The company guarantees that these addresses are not being sold to a third party. The school benefits from about $0.50 for every completed card. This money is used to supplement extra-curricular and service projects (special car seat for a diabled student, buddy bench, snacks for after school programs, etc.).

Monday, February 3 is the final turn in day. Completed booklets equal fun prizes, but partially filled booklets are accepted. Please also return any unfilled booklets. If you have any questions, please direct them to Mr. Nelson at mnelson@skylineschools.org.

post_text:
A reminder from the school nurse-

Please remember that if your child is ill, they must be fever free without the use of fever-reducing medications for 24 hours before returning to school. If your child is vomiting or has diarrhea, they must be symptom free for 24 hours before returning to school.

Persons confirmed to have influenza should stay home for five days following onset of symptoms or until fever free for 24 hours (without the use of fever-reducing medications), whichever is longer, per Kansas requirement. According to CDC, persons with influenza are considered infectious for 5-7 days after becoming sick.

For more information on the flu virus please see http://www.kdheks.gov/flu/ or https://www.cdc.gov/flu/

post_text:
News from the School Nurse:
KDHE recommends that persons who are symptomatic with influenza-like illness (temperature of 100°F (37.8°C] or greater, a cough and/or a sore throat without a known cause other than influenza) and have either a positive laboratory test for influenza or been treated with antiviral medication used to treat influenza is considered to have a case of influenza. To control the spread of influenza the following isolation requirements should be followed:

For each person hospitalized with a case, droplet precautions shall be followed for five days following onset of illness or until fever free for 24 hours without the aid of fever reducing medications, whichever is longer.

For each person with a case shall remain in home isolation for five days following onset of illness or until fever free for 24 hours without the aid of fever reducing medications, whichever is longer, except when seeking medical care. (which means you can leave the house if you are going to the doctor)

post_text:
Kansas School Transportation Appreciation Day - Thanks to Mr. Brown, Ms. Freitas, Mrs. Gigstand, and Mr. Haines!

Governor Laura Kelly has proclaimed Wednesday, October 23, 2019, as School Transportation Appreciation Day.

https://www.kspta.net/

These men and women dedicate their time and talent to make sure our students are safely transported to and from school and activities.

National School Bus Safety Week is October 21-25, 2019. This is the perfect time to contact local members of the media and encourage them to include a story on bus safety – including the importance of obeying the law regarding stopped school buses. With a nationwide shortage of bus drivers, you also may want to ask people to consider applying to become a school bus driver.

Kansas transports more than 218,000 children to and from schools across Kansas every school day. These drivers, dispatchers, mechanics, aides, monitors, directors and other transportation support personnel are extremely valuable assets and are unsung heroes in communities across the state.

The Box Tops for Education program is in the process of transitioning away from clipping Box Tops. In the near future, all Box Top earnings will be earned by digitally scanning receipts through a mobile app. We have tested this app and it is very user-friendly. Once your receipt is scanned, our school receives immediate credit for all Box Top products.

Information detailing the conversion process along with a list of all participating products is attached. We would appreciate your continued support of the Box Tops program. All funds we receive will be used to purchase supplies and materials for STEM projects.

If you have any questions, please let us know. Thank you again for your help in making this program a success!

post_text:
Skyline Families,

We are are so excited for our students to come back to school tomorrow to kick-off A GREAT YEAR AT SKYLINE!

We appreciate that many of our families provide transportation to and from school for their children. For the safety of our students - please use the curb in front of the school to quickly drop-off and pick-up your students. The driver must stay with the vehicle when using the curb to drop-off and pick-up students.

Parents who would like to come in the building with their child are welcome to do so, we would just ask that you park in one of the parking spots in the lot North of the school. We have reserved the entire first row of parking in the North lot for parents and guests. If those parking spots are full, there is almost always space in the gravel lot to the Northwest of the school.

Thank you and we will see you tomorrow morning!

Becca Flowers, Superintendent

Notes from the nurse:

I hope that everyone is enjoying your last few weeks of summer. I am super excited to start the year!

Just a reminder to all to parents and guardians that all Preschool, Kindergarten, 7th grade, and 11th graders have immunization requirements before starting school this year.
If you have questions regarding your student please contact the health department at 672-4135 or me at 672-5651/ email: hmckennon@skylineschools.org. I will also be at enrollment Monday and Tuesday if you need to visit with me about anything.

Medication forms are available online again this year. Your student will need a form signed if you wish to keep prescription or non prescription medications in the health office. If your child needs to carry their own medication you will need to fill out the self administration form and return it to the school. This includes cough drops and over the counter medications.

post_text:
Skyline Families:

As we release our 2019-2020 school supply lists, we remain committed to our ongoing partnership with our families. Skyline will again purchase a majority of the typical school supplies in bulk and provide those for your students. Supply lists will be available on our website this Friday, July 12th. They will also be available at our local Wal-Mart.

Students will still be required to wear tennis shoes to PE. However, if your elementary student opts to wear tennis shoes daily, they can simply wear those shoes for PE. Children who wear sandals, boots, etc will still need to bring a pair of tennis shoes to keep at school. Again, PE shoes to keep at school are not required if your child wears tennis shoes daily.

We hope you are having a fantastic summer break. We are looking forward to having all of our students back in the building on August 27th. If you have any questions or concerns, please let us know!

Sincerely,

Herb McPherson, MS/HS Principal

post_text: Skyline would like to thank all the local businesses and families that support us in so many ways! We know that many local businesses get contacted about sponsoring shirts, mini-basketballs and footballs, towels, water bottles, etc. In order to help our businesses make sure their donations are being used by legitimate fundraising companies, we are now only using one company. They are Better Business Approved. If you are ever contacted by a different company than Sports Promotion Network, they have not been asked by Skyline to do this project. If you have questions, please contact us and we can help you make sure it is a legitimate request. Again, thank you for your continued support! Every T-Bird, Every Day!
